

# DocEngine - PDF to Word Converter & Document Manipulation Suite
DocEngine is a high-performance document processing platform designed to replicate features found on platforms like iLovePDF. It leverages a blazing-fast **C++ Core Engine** for CPU-bound document manipulation, parsing, and OpenXML generation, wrapped inside a **Node.js/Express API Gateway** with a responsive **React/Next.js Frontend**.
---## 🏗️ System Architecture

[React Frontend] ──(HTTP / Multipart)──> [Node.js Express API] ──(Child Process)──> [C++ Core Engine]
│
▼
[Poppler / OpenXML]


- **Frontend**: Handles multi-file slice uploads, real-time progress bars, and drag-and-drop orchestration.
- **Backend API Gateway**: Manages file streams, job queuing, disk isolation via unique UUIDs, and automated cleanups.
- **Core Engine (C++)**: Interacts directly with system binaries and native bindings to perform layout extraction and document reconstruction.

---

## 🛠️ Prerequisites & System Dependencies

Before building the C++ core or booting up the development servers, your system requires native build tools and document development libraries.

### Linux (Ubuntu/Debian)
```bash
sudo apt update
sudo apt install build-essential cmake libpoppler-cpp-dev libreoffice --no-install-recommends
```

### macOS
```bash
brew install cmake poppler libreoffice
```

---

## 🚀 Getting Started

### 1. Compile the C++ Core Engine
The backend gateway expects the compiled executable to reside inside the `cpp-core/bin/` folder.

```bash
# Navigate to the C++ core directory
cd cpp-core

# Create a build directory
mkdir build && cd build

# Generate build files and compile
cmake ..
make

# Move or verify the binary is in the correct path
mkdir -p ../bin
cp pdf_converter ../bin/
cd ../..
```

### 2. Set Up the Backend & Frontend Dependencies
Depending on your chosen execution setup (Node.js/Bun), install the package architecture.

```bash
# Install root package dependencies
npm install

# Initialize Prisma Database Client (if applicable)
npx prisma generate
```

### 3. Run the Application locally
```bash
# Run the development environment
npm run dev
```

---

## 📂 Repository Layout

```filepath
workspace1/
├── cpp-core/             # C++ Source files, CMake configurations, and binary wrappers
│   ├── src/              # Main document converter logic (.cpp files)
│   └── bin/              # Target directory for compiled executable modules
├── src/                  # React/Next.js Application source code
│   ├── components/       # Reusable UI elements (Drag & Drop zones, Progress loops)
│   └── pages/api/        # Express/Next API gateway endpoints
├── db/                   # Database schemas and initialization setups
├── public/               # Asset management, icons, and static images
├── Dockerfile            # Container deployment blueprint for isolated runtime
└── docker-compose.yml    # Multi-container orchestration (App, Database, Cache)
```

---

## 🔧 Roadmap & Feature Implementations

- [x] **PDF to Word Conversion**: Parsing layout absolute boundaries and generating native OpenXML strings.
- [ ] **Merge PDF**: Concatenating discrete PDF streams into consolidated output scopes.
- [ ] **Compress PDF**: Stripping unneeded font metadata and scaling internal `/XObject` images down to 150 DPI.
- [ ] **Word to PDF**: Headless orchestration of background LibreOffice microservices via worker clusters.
- [ ] **Asynchronous Processing**: Integrating a Redis-backed queue hierarchy (`BullMQ`) to handle processing offloading.

---

## 🔒 Security & Optimization Practices

1. **File Sandboxing**: Every job is assigned a strict cryptographic `UUIDv4`. Working directories are automatically deleted upon user stream closure or process failure.
2. **Process Safety**: Inputs processed through the C++ executable layer bypass direct shell execution configurations (`execFile`) to completely eliminate shell-injection risks.
3. **Payload Thresholds**: Global multi-part upload streams are hard-capped at 50MB directly at the edge layer to safeguard system memory structures.

